		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The proposal seeks to explore the potential of optical fibre Bragg grating lasers as acoustic wave (AW) sensors to monitor real time structural integrity based on acousto-ultrasonic or acoustic emission systems. DFB and DBR fibre laser cavities with typical gauge lengths of 2-Scm will be employed. The sensitivity of the cavity to acoustic emission signals in the range IOOkHz to IMHz will be investigated and compared with that of a conventional piezoelectric transducer. The possibility of directional discrimination will be explored. Sensor multiplexing will be addressed with up to three sensors experimentally investigated. This would allow a number of sensors to be positioned along a single fibre as well as the potential implementation as strain rosettes. Factors influencing sensor sensitivity and fidelity such as sensor/host interface coupling and mean strain and noise levels in the structure will be explored to confirm the practical viability of the technique outside the optics laboratory.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
